{"id":"59795d701b69e6006c2af1d0","sn":1499,"u":1514190671119,"c":1501126000258,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Hierarchy of Needs","te":"This picture clearly shows the information about comparison between the fundamental needs model and Abraham Maslow's Hierarchy of needs.
To begin with, the model on the left hand side has three parts which are status needs, simulation needs and security needs, and they are overlapped with each other.
According to this graph, the model on the right hand side has a part named belonging needs, which fits the overlap area of the first model.
Last but not the least, the parts above belonging needs are self-esteem needs and self-actualization needs.
in conclusion, the parts below are safety needs and physiological needs.","i":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/9e7c222c6ff5c288b6e9.png","a1":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/fb8bbce0d183cb1d6942.mp3","a2":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/42c70975aca6b95d615c.mp3","a3":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/5cdfcb467e5ab176cb25.mp3","a4":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/a91e7e46975535de52dd.mp3","a5":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/130d6a7ff2298b69b00b.mp3"}

{"id":"59795e9aa0bb9f0058e5187d","sn":1504,"u":1514190670529,"c":1501126298870,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Rubbish soup","te":"This map diagram shows the approximate areas of rubbish soup in the Pacific Ocean. There are two primary rubbish patches formed by the Pacific Gyre currents. The Eastern rubbish patch lies to the south of China and east of Japan, formed by a gyre current which is rotating counter-clockwise. The western rubbish patch is located off the west coast of Canada and the United States, close to Hawaii. These garbage patches are enormous, almost the size of a whole continent.","i":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/5862ef36edf7f6105b98.png","a1":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/2221767cc839751b4f11.mp3","a2":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/b6c8a937b43773ecef5b.mp3","a3":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/7ca98d84d807c5ea65dc.mp3","a4":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/e0d09cfa8187d506ea94.mp3","a5":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/33166e97a70580e41ffa.mp3"}

{"id":"59ed905567f356003a454fd6","sn":1695,"u":1514190669888,"c":1508741205165,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Pitchback water wheel ","te":"This image shows how the Pitchback water wheel works. First water from a pond, lake or any water section is drawn into the flume, the water flows through the launder and then the wheel rotates in a circle. The water fills up the wooden pockets of the wheel and gravity makes the wheel rotate. {"id":"590d83d2a0bb9f00588de595","sn":1220,"u":1514190666920,"c":1494057938407,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Baby sleep hours","te":"This is a table chart displaying the amount of sleep in hours of baby. There are basically two categories. The first category shows nighttime sleep, daytime sleep and total sleep. The second category shows ages in months. As we can see the hours of sleep for babies changes. As babies grow, their Nighttime sleep hours increase while daytime sleep hours decrease. By combining both nighttime and daytime sleep, the total sleep hours decreases slowly. In conclusion, we can estimate that babies will continue to follow this pattern until they grow older and the sleeping hours will be fixed.","i":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/277903287e48dd628605.jpg","a1":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/84d4113a97190bf1c9d3.mp3","a2":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/65945b4d37dce322d80f.mp3","a3":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/68bc95143021408b8353.mp3","a4":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/342ea9f1a0c618151a2b.mp3","a5":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/a47c10fb92489e8a3de1.mp3"}

{"id":"59ed9408128fe12e51f9d04e","sn":1698,"u":1514190666684,"c":1508742152143,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Virus Replication ","te":"This image exhibits the process of viruses invading a host cell. There are 5 steps. The first is adsorption. The second involves the virus entering the host cell. Then the virus replicates itself in the host cell. {"id":"59795f00a0bb9f0058e51c91","sn":1506,"u":1514190653182,"c":1501126400953,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Total MSW Generation","te":"This graph clearly illustrates the information about total MSW generation by material in 2009.
To begin with, we can see that the categories in comparison  are paper and paperboard, food scraps, yard trimmings, plastics and so on.
According to the graph, the largest proportion goes to paper and paperboard at 28.2%, while the smallest proportion goes to other at 3.5%.
Last but not the least, for the rest of the categories, the number are ranging from 4.8% to 14.1%.

{"id":"597951722f301e0058663044","sn":1492,"u":1514190637886,"c":1501122930625,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Out of sight","te":"This picture illustrates the information of the continent-sized vortex of plastic waste blighting the Pacific Ocean.
To begin with, we can see that on the left of the map, there is a eastern garbage patch near Japan.
According to this graph, we can also see that there is a western garbage patch between Hawaii and North American on the right of the map.
Last but not the least, the two garbage patch are known as the rubbish soup, which is a layer in the ocean composed of degrading plastic wastes.
In conclusion, the layer of garbage was the gyre currents which keep the soup in constant movements and they may further pollute the ocean if there is no action being taken.","i":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/e510f0a19fa81fe27fdc.png","a1":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/42873c35d307b0e3383b.mp3","a2":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/9e6d1515900d87954769.mp3","a3":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/2157956e78b313389b5f.mp3","a4":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/26f794fa4fb262154a72.mp3","a5":"https://dn-JBhPksbU.qbox.me/f06e5d6e56dd001091dc.mp3"}

{"id":"59795e09128fe10056f522fb","sn":1501,"u":1514190610921,"c":1501126153365,"p":"DI","t":"Speaking","q":"Kruse kronicle","te":"This line graph vividly shows the information about the comparison of world income distribution for 1970 and 1990, and the percentage of people earning below the poverty line is one dollar.

According to this graph, because of the growth of population, this percentage of population living under poverty condition declined from 38% to 26%.
Last but not least, in 1990, the majority of the 5.3 billion people in the world were earning less than $10 per day.
In conclusion, the United Nation's goal is to reduce poverty to just 13% by 2015.
